This SPARQL query should return two solutions, both identical, binding variable `?a` to string `"a"`:
```sparql
SELECT * {
    { BIND ("a" AS ?a) }
    UNION
    { BIND ("a" AS ?a) }
}
```
But it returns only one of the two solutions. The same effect—only the first union returns any results—happens when the unions have more than one variable or more than one solution each. The problem is triggered by the _results_ being identical, not just by the _graph patterns_ being identical. This one also just returns one solution:
```sparql
SELECT * {
    { BIND ("a" AS ?a) }
    UNION
    { VALUES ?a { "a" } }
    UNION
    { SELECT ("a" AS ?a) {} }
}
```
The problem goes away as soon as there is any difference between the results of the two union branches.

On fetch.js we have a require call for solid-auth-client but on webpack config is like external, that means that should works if we already import solid-auth-client in our projects, but in this case is not working because will point to internal dependencies.

Here is the issue: 

const auth = require('solid-auth-client')
const fetch = auth ? auth.fetch : (a, b) => window.fetch(a, b)

This works fine on projects where you copy externals script like rdf and solid-auth-client in the bundle but if we want to create a library these libraries should be external to reduce library size and do not have duplicate code.

We can fix it checking if we have solid-auth-client in the context.

const auth = require('solid-auth-client')
const fetch = auth ? auth.fetch : window && solid && solid.auth ? solid.auth.fetch : (a, b) => window.fetch(a, b)

